{[%evp 0,29,27,14,63,41,78,51,51,10,10,11,47,50,43,57,81,29,24,14,70,16,37,25,19,0,-11,-18,-18,-18,-18,-18]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Bxb5 5. cxb5 a6 {A reasonable, although it was only played a few times by strong players. Black is getting rid of b5-pawn and activates his queen's rook. On the the downside, it often assists White in making passer on the queenside.} 6. bxa6 (6. d4 Nf6 7. bxa6 Nxa6 {may transpose to text, but it also yields Black some extra options.}) 6... Nxa6 ({For some reason,} 6... Rxa6 {is Black's top choice by far. It looks somewhat artificial and makes White's task much easier:} 7. d4 cxd4 {it hardly makes sense to leave White with such powerful centre/} 8. Nxd4 g6 ({After} 8... Nc6 9. Nb5 Nf6 10. N1c3 e6 11. Bf4 {White's positional advantage is undenieble.}) 9. O-O Bg7 10. Nc3 Nf6 {Both sides consistently mobilize their forces.} 11. Be3 O-O 12. Qe2 Nc6 {This position was reached in Naroditsky, D - Lewtak, D Chess.com INT 2022 Here White should have continued} 13. Ndb5 $146 Qd7 14. Rad1 Ng4 15. Bf4 {Black's poor piece coordination makes their position difficult.}) 7. d4 g6 ({The only adequate alternative is} 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 9. Nc3 e6 {Black covers d5, but weakens d6.} 10. O-O Be7 11. Qe2 O-O 12. Rd1 $14 {White has easy play against opponent's weak d6-pawn.}) 8. O-O Bg7 9. Nc3 Nf6 $1 {It makes sense for Black to maintain the tension in centre.} ({Less precise is} 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nf6 11. Be3 O-O 12. f3 Qa5 13. a3 Rfc8 14. Rc1 {White's pawn majority on the queenside is supported by active pieces. Black has to struggle for equality. Martinez Alcantara,J - Sliwicka,A Chess.com INT 2022}) 10. Be3 Ng4 ({In the event of} 10... O-O 11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. e5 Ng4 13. Bxc5 dxc5 14. Qe2 $14 {Black's position seems uncomfortable in view of blocked g7-bishop and weak b5-spot.}) 11. Bg5 {This reminds us of Najdorf 6.Be3 Ng4. Of course, White should deviate from exchanging such a strong bishop.} h6 12. Bh4 O-O 13. h3 {It is time to drive away the nasty knight.} cxd4 ({Worse is} 13... Nf6 $6 14. e5 Nh5 15. Nd5 {Activity of White's pieces is getting threatening. For instance,} Re8 16. exd6 Qxd6 17. dxc5 Qxc5 18. Rc1 {Black suffers material losses.}) 14. Nxd4 Ne5 15. Ndb5 {This position was reached in Coles, J-Santoso, L ICCF email 2019. In my opinion, White has somewhat more comfortable play due to strong b5-knight and queenside pawn majority, although Black maintains definite counterplay due to fianchettoed bishop.} *

