{[%evp 0,35,23,23,51,51,77,47,47,10,10,13,11,18,14,15,15,13,13,10,9,9,14,16,13,8,2,-29,-1,10,10,19,3,7,5,12,7,22]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Bxb5 5. cxb5 Nf6 6. Nc3 g6 {A common move. Black opts for fianchetto and intends to claim drawbacks of White's pawn structure by pushing ...d6-d5 in the long run.} ({The other possibilities are:} 6... a6 7. bxa6 Nxa6 8. d4 e6 ({Another possible transposition is} 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 g6 10. O-O Bg7) (8... g6 9. O-O {trasnposes to 4...Bxb5 & 5...a6.}) 9. O-O Be7 10. Qe2 $1 {White overprotects e4 and vacates d1 for his rook.} O-O 11. Rd1 {The opposition on the d-file is definitely annoying for Black.} d5 ({Hardly better is} 11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Qa5 13. Ndb5 $14) 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 exd5 ({The attempt to deviate from isolated pawn with} 13... Qxd5 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Be3 Qc7 16. a3 $14 {leaves Black in an inferior position with awkward a6-knight, when White's pieces are fully mobilized.}) 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Be3 {Black had no compensation for his inferior pawn structure in Serner, A - Eschert, U ICCF email 2017}) (6... e6 {A solid, but somewhat passive way of development.} 7. d4 cxd4 (7... Nbd7 {doesn't change much:} 8. O-O cxd4 9. Nxd4 Be7 10. Qe2 O-O {with a transposition.}) 8. Nxd4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe2 {The queen is well-placed, when the key pawns e4 and b5 are covered.} Nbd7 11. Rd1 Rc8 {This position occurred in 3 high-level games, including Harikrishna - Negi. Here I suggest the following conceptual idea:} 12. a4 $5 $146 {White intents to push a4-a5-a6, claiming weak c6-spot in opponent's camp.} Qa5 {This stops a4-a5 for now.} ({After} 12... Qc7 13. a5 Rfe8 14. a6 $36 {Black is under strong pressure on the queenside.}) 13. Bd2 Qb6 14. Nb3 {White has a big space advantage and decent prospects with the above-mentioned a4-a5-a6 push.}) (6... Nbd7 7. O-O g6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 {leads to the same positions as 6...g6 with ...Nbd7 at later stage.}) (6... e5 {This way of preventing traditional d2-d4 is strategically risky as it yields White permanent control over light squares.} 7. d3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. a4 Nbd7 ({After} 9... a6 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 12. Qb3 $14 {Black suffers from passive e7-bishop and weak d5-spot.}) 10. Nh4 g6 11. Nf3 Nh5 12. Bh6 Re8) (6... d5 $2 {This break in centre is certainly premature.} 7. e5 Ne4 8. e6 $1 {A thematic advance - White interrupts the opponent's natural development.} f6 ({After} 8... fxe6 9. Qe2 Nxc3 10. dxc3 {White's development advantage is nearly decisive.}) 9. Qe2 Nxc3 10. dxc3 {Black struggles to complete development. White should be able to develop a crushing attack anytime soon. Shirazi, K - Grover, S Paris 2008}) 7. O-O Bg7 8. d4 {White should play this move if it is allowed.} cxd4 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. Qe2 {There are some good-looking alternatives, but I would like to stick with a traditional setup: White's heavy pieces will be placed harmoniously.} Nbd7 ({The attempt to clear c6 for the knight by means of} 10... a6 $6 11. Rd1 axb5 {runs into} 12. e5 $1 Ne8 13. Ndxb5 {, and Black is too cramped.}) 11. Rd1 Rc8 (11... Qc7 {Black connects his rooks, but the queen is vulnerable now.} 12. Be3 Rfc8 13. Rac1 {Now Black has to waste another tempo for moving the queen.} Qd8 {This was Landa,K - Woudsma,M Vlissingen 2017 Here I mostly like the conceptual} 14. a4 $146 Qa5 ({In the event of} 14... a6 15. bxa6 bxa6 16. b4 {White's passer on the queenside prevails.}) 15. Bd2 Qb6 16. Nb3 $14 {White intends to grab more space with a4-a5-a6 and at some point occupy c6. Black's counterplay is questionable.}) (11... a6 12. Be3 Qa5 {doesn't provide Black any constructive counter-attacking possibilities, while the queen becomes vulnerable.} 13. Nb3 Qc7 14. Rac1 {White involves all his pieces with tempi. The promising opposition along the c-file and weak b6-spot in Black's camp provides some tactical resources, such as} Rfc8 15. e5 $5 {Not only, but elegant way of claiming advantage.} Nxe5 ({Worse is} 15... dxe5 $2 16. Nd5 Qd8 17. Rxc8 Rxc8 18. Nxf6+ $18 {with 19.Qd2 to follow.}) 16. Nd5 Qd8 17. Bb6 Qf8 18. Nc7 {Black suffers material losses. Cozianu,C - Istratescu,A Timisu de Sus 1998}) 12. h3 {White makes room for his king and secures e3 by eliminating ...Ng4.} ({Less effective is} 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Re8 14. Rac1 Qb6 {Black was fine in Xiong, J - Korchmar, V Chess.com INT 2020}) 12... Nc5 {The most challenging response. Black puts more pressure on e4 and signals that he wants to play ...d6-d5 at some point.} ({After} 12... Qc7 13. Be3 Qc4 14. Qd2 $14 {Black's queen turns misplaced in view of ..Rac1. Abbas,D - Guerra Bastida,D Pontevedra 2014}) 13. a4 e6 ({In the event of} 13... Nfd7 14. Ra3 Ne6 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. a5 {, followed by 17.Be3 Black struggles to neutralize White's pressure on queenside pawns.}) ({Also after} 13... Qa5 14. Bd2 Qc7 15. Bg5 e6 16. Qe3 $14 {White is firmly in control because most of Black's pieces are very passive.}) 14. a5 {From now Black has to deal with .. a5-a6 with further occupation of c6. Also, it takes a5 from Black's queen.} e5 15. Nf3 Nb3 {This was the point of Black's previous committing move.} 16. Rb1 Nxc1 17. Rbxc1 Qxa5 18. Rxd6 {Despite major simplifications Black still has some issues to solve because White's pieces are more active and e5-pawn is vulnerable.} *

