{[%evp 0,37,23,23,51,66,77,41,44,10,30,29,55,59,44,44,64,53,47,40,35,40,43,38,30,35,39,43,40,39,34,35,35,38,36,9,10,41,41,14]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 a6 {Black decides to force the immediate exchange on d7. It can be hardly considered as a loss of tempo because it assists Black in initiating actions on the queenside with b7-b5.} 5. Bxd7+ {There is an equal choice between 5...Nxd7 and Qxd7.} Qxd7 {This recapture is as common as 5...Nxd7.} 6. Nc3 Nc6 (6... e6 {usually doesn't have an independent value} 7. O-O Nf6 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Be7 {Black keeps the queen's knight on its initial spot for a while} 10. Be3 {White opts for the traditional setup with Qe2 and Rad1.} O-O 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. f4 Rc8 (12... Nbd7 $6 {is too passive and runs into} 13. g4 $1 Nc5 14. Qg2 {with a powerful initiative.}) (12... Nc6 13. Rad1 {transposes to 6...Nc6.}) 13. b3 Nbd7 {Rublevsky, S - Perun, S Smolensk 2000 Now it makes sense to prevent any activity of Black on the queenside with} 14. Rac1 $146 Bf8 15. Qf3 Re8 16. g4 g6 17. Nde2 {Black's king is under long-termed pressure as f4-f5 is in the air.}) ({In the event of} 6... Nf6 {White can claim the weak b6-spot by means of} 7. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 {Csiki,E - Gu,X Budapest 2024} 8. cxd5 $146 g6 9. d4 {Black lacks harmony, and the b8-knight is blocked.} Bg7 10. dxc5 dxc5 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 $14) 7. O-O {The most flexible. White will most likely play d2-d4, but there are also some other options at his disposal.} Nf6 (7... g6 {took place in a couple of games. Here I like the following creative idea:} 8. b4 $5 $146 {White takes advantage of superior development and sacrifices a pawn.} cxb4 ({After} 8... Nxb4 9. d4 Bg7 10. Rb1 {there is lots of pressure on the b-file.}) 9. Nd5 Bg7 10. d4 {White gains a crucial tempo in view of the threat of 11.Nb6.} Rb8 11. a3 {A-la Benko gambit!} bxa3 12. Re1 Nf6 ({In the event of} 12... e6 13. Bxa3 exd5 14. cxd5 $36 {White regains material and maintains strong pressure due to powerful centre.}) 13. Nxf6+ exf6 14. Bxa3 {White has full compensation for the pawn, to say the least.}) 8. d4 {After all this is the most ambitious way of handling the position.} cxd4 9. Nxd4 e6 {This position is a sort of tabiya that can be reached with different move orders.} ({Inaccurate is} 9... g6 $6 10. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 11. exd5 Ne5 12. b3 $16 {Black was positionally busted in Erenburg, S - Luo, T ICC INT 2020}) (9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 e6 11. b3 Be7 12. Ba3 Qc7 {took place in Larrua Gonzalez,F - Morales Romero,P Havana 2013 In my opinion, White could have increased pressure on the d6-pawn by means of} 13. Rad1 $146 Rd8 14. Bb4 O-O 15. h3 Rfe8 16. Rd3 $14) 10. Be3 Be7 11. Qe2 {The most harmonious setup - White covers both c4 and e4 and supports the further extension with f2-f4 and e4-e5 or f4-f5. Also, White vacates d1 for his rooks.} O-O 12. Rad1 {I like this natural approach. White keeps the rook on f1 in order to push f2-f4 at some point.} ({The most common alternative is} 12. Rfd1 {, but it means White isn't going to act on the kingside anytime soon.}) 12... Rac8 (12... Qc7 13. f4 Rac8 {is another possible moves order.}) ({After} 12... Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Qc6 14. f4 Rac8 15. b3 {makes it easier for White to extend on the kingside due to the strong d4-bishop.} Rfe8 16. e5 dxe5 17. fxe5 Nd7 18. Qg4 {Black's king got under strong pressure in Edwards, K - Catarineu Rabell, M ICCF email 2010}) (12... Rfc8 {also makes Black's kingside more vulnerable} 13. f4 Qc7 14. b3 Qa5 15. Nxc6 {White vacates d4 for his bishop again.} Rxc6 16. Bd4 Nd7 17. Rd3 {White has excellent attacking prospects. Gubanov, A - Nepomnishay, M St Petersburg 1997}) 13. f4 Qc7 14. b3 {There are a few ways to reach this position.} Qa5 {The most common choice. By attacking c3-knight Black makes the possible ...b7-b5 break more attractive.} ({In the event of} 14... Rfe8 {white can favorably stabilize situation in centre by means of} 15. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 (15... Qxc6 16. Bf2 Nd7 17. Bd4 $14) 16. Rc1 $1 {An accurate way to prevent ...d6-d5.} Nd7 ({After} 16... Qb7 $6 17. e5 dxe5 18. fxe5 Nd7 19. Qh5 $36 {White's initiative is very powerful.}) 17. Qd3 {White has somewhat more space and Black's counterplay with d6-d5 is problematic. It will be not easy to make further progress on the kingside, but White's practical task is easier.}) ({After} 14... Nxd4 15. Bxd4 e5 16. fxe5 dxe5 17. Be3 b5 18. Nd5 Nxd5 19. cxd5 {White has a clear structural advantage, although it is not so easy to make progress.}) ({Too passive is} 14... Rfd8 15. g4 Nd7 16. g5 {White takes the upper hand on the kingside. Pedro, F - Galvin, J LSS email 2013}) 15. Nxc6 bxc6 ({After} 15... Rxc6 16. Bd4 Rd8 17. Kh1 {White was well-prepared for starting actions with g2-g4, f4-f5, e.t.c. El Debs,F - Correa,A Caioba 2016}) 16. Bd2 Qc7 {We have been following the game Ralls, N - Wurschner, M LSS email 2006 Here I suggest the most ambitious} 17. e5 dxe5 18. fxe5 Nd7 19. Bf4 $14 {White has superiority in space and decent attacking prospects.} *

