{[%evp 0,25,23,17,66,41,77,44,37,10,34,35,26,23,22,27,34,14,12,-6,-8,-43,-20,-19,-26,-44,-26,-31]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 a6 5. Bxd7+ Nxd7 6. Nc3 Ngf6 (6... e6 7. O-O Ngf6 {is another possible moves order.}) (6... g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. d3 Ngf6 {is another transposition.}) 7. O-O e6 {The most common choice.} ({The alternative way of development is} 7... g6 8. d3 {As after 7... e6 I prefer this modest-looking move.} (8. d4 {is traditionally White's main attempt to claim an advantage. However, after} cxd4 9. Nxd4 Rc8 10. Qe2 Bg7 {Black seems to have enough counterplay. For instance,} 11. Bd2 O-O 12. Rac1 Qb6 13. Be3 Nxe4 $1 {invites major complications that are acceptable for Balck.}) 8... Bg7 9. h3 {White secures e3 for his bishop by eliminating ...Ng4.} O-O 10. Be3 e6 {Black declares his intent to initiate active play in centre with ... d6-d5.} ({In the event of} 10... Rb8 11. a4 Ne8 {Black focuses on preparing ... b7-b5, but now it gives white the upper hand in centre because of passive e8-knight} 12. d4 $1 cxd4 13. Nxd4 (13. Bxd4 $5 {is another decent option.}) 13... Ne5 14. b3 Nc7 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Markidis,K - Tsarsitalidis,K Agios Ioannis 2018 Here I suggest} 15. Rc1 $146 Nc6 16. Nf3 $1 $14 {Whtie manages to avoid simplifications, that are favorable for Black who lacks space.}) 11. Qd2 {White has reached an optimal setup when his rooks are connected. One of the possible ideas may be ...Bh6 because the exchange of bishops will make Black's king quite exposed.} Qc7 {This position was recently reached in Klimkowski, J - Duda, J Chess.com INT 2024} (11... Rc8 {was played by a few strong players, including Ivanchuk. In my opinion, White can fully focus on attacking actions with} 12. Rae1 $5 $146 Ne5 13. Nh2 Nc6 14. f4 $14 {Black doesn't seem to have sufficient counterplay.}) {Now I suggest the flexible} 12. Rab1 $5 $146 {White is interested in seizing more space with b2-b4 and also preventing Black from doing the same with...b7-b5.} Rfd8 ({Hardly better is} 12... Rfe8 13. Bh6 Bh8 14. Nh2 $14) 13. Bh6 d5 {This looks like Black's only way to emerge counterplay. However, after} ({After} 13... Bh8 14. Ng5 $1 d5 15. cxd5 exd5 16. f4 $36 {White's attacking prospects prevail.}) 14. cxd5 exd5 15. Qg5 dxe4 (15... d4 16. Ne2 {also leaves White with decent attacking prospects.}) 16. dxe4 {White's pawn majority on the kingside and more active pieces make Black's position uncomfortable.}) (7... Rc8 {This move is only sensible in case White play d2-d4.} 8. d3 e6 9. Kh1 (9. Ne1 $5 {is a similar approach: nothing can prevent White from pushing the kingside pawns.}) 9... Be7 10. Ng1 {is an improved version for White, compared to 7... e6 because Ra8-c8 is a sort of wasted move. A likely continuation is:} Ne5 11. f4 Nc6 12. Qf3 $1 {white transfers his queen on h3, were it will increase the effect of g2-g4.} Nd4 13. Qh3 Nd7 14. g4 {Black's kingside is under long-termed pressure.}) 8. d3 $5 {I like this modest move. White deviates from occupying the centre and maintains the tension.} ({Instead,} 8. d4 {is much more common, but after} cxd4 9. Nxd4 Rc8 10. Qe2 Be7 {Black has lots of counterplay against c4.}) 8... Be7 9. Kh1 $5 {This rare move is connected with a clear plan: White vacates g1 for his knight in order to start expansion with f2-f4 and g2-g4.} O-O 10. Ng1 Ne5 $1 {This strong move hasn't been played so far. Black relocates his knight on c6, where it will be placed much more actively.} ({Premature is} 10... d5 {Kilgus,G - Miron,L Chess.com INT 2020} 11. cxd5 $1 exd5 12. f4 d4 13. Nce2 {White has excellent attacking prospects.}) ({Too slow is} 10... Rb8 {Laiz Ibanez,H - Fier,A Sanxenxo 2022} 11. f4 b5 12. Qe2 bxc4 13. dxc4 {Black doesn't seem to have enough play on the queenside, while White has a few promising ideas, including g2-g4-g5 and e4-e5.}) 11. f4 Nc6 12. g4 Nd7 13. g5 {This complex middlegame offer interesting play for both sides. Even so, White's practical task seems easier because of the potential strong attack on Black's king.} *

