{[%evp 0,25,21,11,41,39,82,41,41,10,20,20,31,10,34,34,37,27,43,6,66,6,66,-11,10,7,37,31]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 e5 {Black radically prevents d2-d4, but it costs him weakening d5. Also, the f8-bishop is somewhat problematic from now.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 (5... Nc6 {tranposes to 4...Nc6 & e5}) ({it hardly makes much sense to start with} 5... Be7 6. d3 Bxb5 (6... Nc6 {transposes to 4...Nc6 & 5...e5}) 7. cxb5 Nd7 8. O-O h6 ({After} 8... Ngf6 {White has many promising possibilities, including} 9. Nh4 $5 g6 {Black cannot let White host the knight on f5.} 10. g3 O-O 11. Ng2 $14 {White takes control of d5. Also, Black's kingside is somewhat committed after ...g7-g6.}) 9. Nd2 Ngf6 10. Nc4 {White is ready to take the upper hand on the kingside with f2-f4. Naroditsky, D - Macaspac, A Rancho Mirage 2022}) 6. d3 Be7 (6... Nc6 {again transposes to 4...Nc6 & e5.}) 7. Bxd7+ {It hardly makes sense for White to keep the b5-bishop on the board - it did its job.} Qxd7 {Black is interested in placing the knight on c6, where it hass access to d4.} (7... Nbxd7 {is too passive. White has few ways to claim superiority when I mostly like the energetic} 8. O-O O-O 9. Nh4 $1 Nxe4 {This tactical response doesn't really change much.} ({Even worse is} 9... Re8 10. Nf5 Bf8 11. f4 {, and White's initiative is lasting itself.}) 10. dxe4 Bxh4 11. Qxd6 {White dominates due to control of d5 and pressure on Black's pawns c5 and e5. Avellan, G - Gaitan Moyano,J LSS email 2013}) 8. a3 {White declares his intent to grab some space with b2-b4.} Nc6 9. Rb1 a5 ({An equal alternative is} 9... O-O 10. b4 b6 11. O-O {, and now Black is invited to show his cards:} Nd4 ({After} 11... Ne8 12. Nd5 f5 13. Qa4 $1 {Black has no time for developing adequate counterplay on the kingside. For instance,} Rc8 14. bxc5 bxc5 15. Qa6 $36 {White is ready for further extension on the queenside with ..Rb7. Vokhidov, S - Kalashian, D Chess. com INT 2020}) 12. Bg5 Ne8 {The natural play by both sides led to this position in Iordachescu, V - Kosanovic, G Bucharest 1997 Now the simple} 13. Nxd4 $146 cxd4 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Nd5 {, followed by f2-f4 would have offered White has a clear advantage due to superiority in pawn structure and very strong knight.}) 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne1 Nd4 ({Black's pieces arere quite crumped also after} 11... Ne8 12. Nd5 Bd8 13. f4 a4 14. Nc2 {Churkina,N-Malashenkov,A ICCF email 2013}) 12. Nc2 Nxc2 13. Qxc2 {White has a clear positional advantage due to a superior bishop. Black can hardly prevent the nasty f2-f4. Ciocaltea, V-Notaros,K Novi Sad 1973} *

