{[%evp 0,29,24,11,39,36,66,38,41,11,10,10,10,5,58,25,44,9,7,-8,-8,-2,-15,-20,17,-10,29,15,22,-8,14,-8]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Nc6 5. Nc3 e5 {This is Black's 3rd choice. It leads to a very closed position when both sides struggle to make progress on any side of the board. Even so, White benefits from having somewhat more active pieces.} 6. d3 {Now Black is at a crossroads. There are a few ways of development at his disposal.} Nge7 {A flexible move. Now Black can choose between 6...Ng6, followed by Be7 or 6...g6.} ({The alternatives are:} 6... Nf6 7. a3 Be7 {is another possible moves order.}) (6... Be7 7. a3 Nf6 ({I've also examined} 7... a5 $5 8. O-O Nf6 9. Nh4 $1 {The most ambitious choice. White's knight will land on f5 and force Black to concess his light-squared bishop.} O-O 10. Nf5 Bxf5 11. exf5 Nd4 12. g4 {a complex struggle is ahead, but White's play seems more pleasant due to control over light squares and potential expansion with g4-g5.}) 8. h3 O-O 9. O-O Ne8 {This position took place in a few high-level games.} ({Hardly better is} 9... a5 10. Bd2 Ne8 {Black transfers the knight on c7 and blocks his f-pawn.} 11. Ba4 {A decent prophylactic move.} Nc7 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. exd5 Nb8 14. b4 {White took the upper hand on the queenside in Klimczak, J - Egelstaff, R ICCF email 2019}) {Now I find the most ambiitous} 10. b4 $5 $146 cxb4 {This is the only challenging reaction.} ({After} 10... b6 11. bxc5 bxc5 12. Nd5 Nc7 13. Bd2 {White has a slight, but long-lasting positional advantage.}) 11. axb4 Nxb4 12. Ba3 {All White's minor pieces are active now.} Nc6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. c5) (6... g6 {is another natural continuation, but it makes it easier for White to extend initiative with b2-b4.} 7. a3 Bg7 ({Ineffective is} 7... a5 8. Nd5 Bg7 9. O-O h6 {The immediate 9...Nf6 runs into 10.Bg5!} 10. Bd2 Nf6 11. b4 $14 {White takes the upper hand on queenside anyway.}) 8. b4 Nge7 ({Bad is} 8... cxb4 $2 9. axb4 Nxb4 10. Ba3 {, and Black is on the verge of collapse.}) 9. bxc5 dxc5 10. Rb1 {A useful move. Black will have to take care of b7 sooner or later.} O-O 11. O-O b6 12. h3 $14 {it is only a matter of time before White will occupy d5 and push a3-a4-a5. Black's counterplay is questionable.}) 7. h4 $1 {This move heavily restricts Black's options. In many cases White may deprive Black's knight of g6.} h5 {A double-edged decision. Black prevents the nasty h4-h5 but weakens his pawn chain.} (7... f5 8. h5 {leaves Black very crumped on the kingside.} f4 9. a3 a6 {This was Svane,F - Sarana,A Chess.com INT 2022 White should have continued} 10. Ba4 $1 $146 Nc8 11. b4 cxb4 12. Nd5 {, obtaining powerful initiative.}) ({The timid} 7... h6 {Alekseenko,K - Muradli, M Biel 2022 can be well met by} 8. Nh2 $5 $146 {White's knight moves towards d5, and the f2-pawn is unblocked now.} g6 (8... Ng6 {doesn't fully solve development issues because of} 9. h5 Nf4 10. Bxf4 exf4 11. Qd2 $14 {, and the f4-pawn is very vulnerable.}) 9. h5 g5 ({After} 9... Bg7 10. hxg6 fxg6 11. Nf1 Nd4 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Ne3 $14 {White has a somewhat better pawn structure, and the bishop is more active than Black's bishop.}) 10. g4 $1 {Without ...f7-f5 Black struggles to make any counter-play.} Bg7 11. Nf1 O-O 12. Ne3 {The knight has reached its destination.} a6 13. Bxc6 Nxc6 14. Ncd5 $14 {Black's position is solid but very passive.}) 8. Bg5 f6 9. Be3 g6 ({The alternative} 9... a6 10. Ba4 Rb8 11. a3 {hardly makes much sense as Black still cannot play ...b7-b5, and their development remains problematic.}) 10. a3 Bg7 {we have been following Robson, R - Vachier Lagrave, M Saint Louis 2023 Now the most consistent was} 11. b4 $146 b6 ({In case of} 11... cxb4 $6 12. axb4 Nxb4 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. Rxa7 Rxa7 15. Bxa7 {White's structural advantage is very significant.}) 12. Nd5 O-O ({After} 12... Nxd5 13. cxd5 Nd4 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7 15. Nd2 {Black's position seems quite dangerous from a strategic point of view because of passive g7-bishop and White's clear play with a3-a4-a5.}) 13. bxc5 dxc5 ({Worse is} 13... bxc5 $6 14. Qa4 Rc8 15. O-O $36 {White's play along the b-file is lasting itself.}) 14. Nd2 Be6 15. Nb3 {White has decent prospects on the queenside, when a3-a4-a5 may weaken b6. Of course, in the long run, it will be not easy to make further progress, but Black's counterplay is questionable because f6-f5 gives up control of g5.} *

