{[%evp 0,31,21,11,36,45,68,39,39,10,5,5,25,37,35,23,23,17,14,32,26,26,26,25,34,24,33,20,32,32,38,45,60,43]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Nc6 5. Nc3 g6 {A flexible continuation. Black opts for a fianchetto in order to take more control of d4.} 6. Bxc6 {A well-timed exchange that diminishes Black's control of d4.} Bxc6 ({It makes a little sense to play} 6... bxc6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 Nf6 ({Even worse is} 8... f6 $6 9. c5 e5 10. Qc4 $36) 9. c5 $1 dxc5 ({After} 9... Bg4 10. Qa4 Bxf3 11. gxf3 {Black's queenside pawns are in big danger.}) 10. Qxc5 Qb6 ({In the event of} 10... Bg7 11. Be3 O-O 12. O-O {Black struggles to connect his rooks because of pressure on e7.}) 11. Be3 Qxc5 ({After} 11... Qxb2 $2 12. Rb1 Qc2 13. Qc4 {Black suffers heavy material losses in view of 14.Nd4.}) 12. Bxc5 {Black has no compensation for his structural drawbacks.}) 7. d4 cxd4 (7... Bg7 {is connected with a major strategic risk.} 8. d5 Bd7 9. h3 {White has huge space advantage, and it makes sense to preserve as many pieces as possible.} a6 {Black builds his counterplay on ...b7-b5 break, but this is too artificial.} 10. O-O b5 {Kovalev,V - Orozbaev,E Moscow 2018} 11. Re1 $146 {I like this simple approach - White declares his intent to push e4-e5.} Qc7 ({After} 11... bxc4 12. e5 {Black fails to complete his development.}) ({Or} 11... b4 12. Ne2 Nf6 13. e5 dxe5 14. Nxe5 {White just dominates over the board. Black's bishop does not seem to play any role in this situation.}) 12. Qd3 bxc4 13. Qxc4 {After ..e4-e5 White's lead in development will become nearly the decisive factor.}) 8. Nxd4 Bg7 9. Be3 Nf6 10. f3 {White reaches a harmonious setup when Black's light-squared bishop is well-restricted, and any attempt to make counterplay with ...b7-b5 or d6-d5 is problematic.} O-O 11. O-O {This position a-la Marocy was reached in a couple of high-level games. As the practical test proves, Black can basically sit and wait.} Qa5 ({The other possibilities are:} 11... a6 12. Qd2 Rc8 13. Rac1 Bd7 14. b3 Qa5 {Black is trying to prepare ...b7-b5, but it isn't enough.} 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16. a4 Be8 17. Nde2 e6 18. Bd4 {Black is left with weak d6-pawn and poor bishop on e8. Neiksans,A - Shirov,A Jurmala 2016}) (11... Nd7 12. Qd2 Re8 13. Rac1 a5 14. b3 Ne5 ({Also after} 14... Nc5 15. Rfd1 Qb6 16. Kh1 {White can slowly prepare b3-b4 or choose a proper moment for occupying d5.}) 15. Rfd1 {Black was doomed to passive defence as it often happens in Marocy structures. Naroditsky,D - Dubov,D Chess.com INT 2022}) (11... Rc8 12. Qd2 Re8 {By covering e7 Black makes Qd8-a5 possible, but this isn't a big achievement.} 13. Rac1 Qa5 14. Rfd1 {As usual, White spots his rook in centre.} a6 15. b3 Bd7 16. a4 {Black faced traditional space issues, when there is nothing better than sitting and waiting. Zoler,D - Beliavsky,A Yerevan 2014}) 12. Qd2 Rfc8 {This is the most flexible setup in Maroczy type of positions. Black maintains both his rooks on the queenside and potential ... Qd8 will not disconnect them.} 13. Rac1 Be8 ({Hardly better is} 13... Nd7 14. b3 Nc5 15. Rb1 Qd8 16. Rfd1 $14 {White can either prepare ..b3-b4 or opt for .. Nc3-d5, provoking Black to weaken his pawn chain with e7-e6.}) 14. b3 a6 15. a4 $1 {As usual, depriving Black of only active idea with b7-b5.} e6 16. Rfd1 $14 {The weak d6-pawn seems to cause Black long-term issues. Neiksans,A - Khalifman, A Liepaja 2015} *

