{[%evp 0,31,27,18,45,45,61,39,39,5,5,5,6,6,9,5,5,-44,-16,-24,-24,-29,-13,4,2,-8,49,39,44,8,20,9,29,26]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Nc6 {This is Black's second choice after 4...Nf6. Its main point is eliminating ..Bxd7+, so most likely White will have to capture on c6.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. O-O e5 {leads to a closed position, in similar to 5...e5. However, in this case, Black's setup is less flexible because Ng8-f6 is already played.} (6... e6 {is Black's second choice after 6...g6.} 7. Bxc6 $5 {I like this conceptual idea: in Marocy pawn structures White's light-squared bishop is often not so active, so White is happy to exchange it at early stage.} (7. d4 {is much more common.}) 7... Bxc6 8. Qe2 Be7 9. d4 {It is a good moment for extending in centre.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. b3 {This is already a rare position that was only seen in a couple of games.} a6 {Black can hardly do without this move in the long run.} ({In the event of} 11... Rc8 12. Bb2 Nd7 13. Rad1 a6 14. f4 {White has big space advantage and decent attacking prospects.}) 12. Bb2 Qc7 13. Rad1 Rfe8 {A decent move. Favorable opposition on the e-file makes it possible for Black to break with d6-d5 at some point.} 14. h3 $1 {The main point of this move is diminishing the effect of ...d6-d5.} Rad8 15. f4 Nd7 ({After} 15... d5 16. cxd5 exd5 17. e5 Ne4 18. Kh2 {White covers g3 and stands better due to superior pawn structure and poor c6-bishop.}) 16. Rf3 Nc5 17. Kh2 $14 {A long struggle is ahead, but White's play is easier.}) (6... a6 {is a sensible move, although White is mostly ready to capture c6 anyway.} 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. Re1 e5 (8... g6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bg7 {also took place, including a few top-level games. Here I suggest the following new idea:} 11. Bf4 $5 $146 {White signals that he wants to play e4-e5 at some point.} Rc8 (11... Nd7 {diminishes Black's control of e4 and allows White to reach a harmonious setup with} 12. Be3 O-O 13. Rc1 Rc8 14. f3 Qa5 15. Re2 $14 {Black suffers from lack of space.}) 12. Rc1 O-O 13. Nxc6 Rxc6 ({Also after} 13... bxc6 14. e5 dxe5 15. Bxe5 {White has a slightly better pawn structure and more active pieces.}) 14. b3 Nd7 15. Nd5 $14 {The e7-pawn is a long-term weakness.}) 9. b4 $5 $146 cxb4 ({Quieter is} 9... b6 10. bxc5 bxc5 11. Rb1 Be7 12. d3 O-O 13. Re2 $1 {, followed by Reb2 White has an easy play on the queenside. Black's bishop pair doesn't seem to play an important role here.}) 10. Nd5 Bxd5 11. cxd5 Be7 12. d4 {White has promising play for the pawn due to superiority in centre and piece coordination. For instance,} Nd7 13. Bb2 Bf6 14. Qa4 {with initiative.}) (6... Nd4 {is a radical way of preventing d3-d4. On the downside, it significantly delays Black's development} 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. d3 Nxf3+ 9. Qxf3 g6 ({After} 9... e6 10. Bd2 Be7 11. Qh3 $1 O-O 12. f4 {Black struggles to make any counterplay on the queenside, while White's expansion is fast.}) 10. Qe2 $1 {The same approach - White is aiming to quickly push f2-f4. Curiously, this natural move was only seen in a few games so far.} Bg7 11. f4 O-O 12. f5 $36 {Black's position feels rather cramped - g2-g4-g5 is to follow soon.}) 7. d3 Be7 8. Nh4 $5 {This time I prefer this aggressive approach over the traditional plan with a2-a3 and b2-b4.} O-O ({Hardly including} 8... a6 9. Ba4 {is a good idea because a6 is more vulnerable. For instance,} Bg4 10. f3 Be6 11. Nf5 O-O 12. Nxe7+ Qxe7 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qa4 $14 {Black's queenside pawns are vulnerable, and White can initiative active play on the kingside with f3-f4 at any moment. Sogin, D - Ryan, P ICCF email 2022}) ({Another possibility is} 8... Bg4 9. f3 Be6 10. Nf5 {White is fine with the arising pawn structure.} Bxf5 11. exf5 O-O 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. g4 Re8 14. Kh1 {We have been following the correspondence game Wegelin, R - Vega Palma, M ICCF email 2022. White has the more pleasant game because of attacking prospects, while Black's counterplay on the queenside is questionable.}) 9. Bxc6 {It makes sense to get a rid of useless bishop before Black plays ...Nd4.} bxc6 (9... Bxc6 $6 10. Nf5 $36 {, followed by f2-f4 looks very unpleasant for Black.}) 10. Nf5 Ne8 11. Nxe7+ $146 {White deprives opponent of bishop pair and weakens d6.} ({Instead,} 11. f4 Bf6 $1 12. Qf3 Rb8 13. Rb1 Nc7 $132 {was unclear in Tari,A - Vachier Lagrave,M Stavanger 2022}) 11... Qxe7 12. f4 exf4 ({After} 12... f5 13. Qf3 $1 Nf6 14. h3 Rae8 15. Bd2 {Black has no compensation for structural drawbacks on the queenside.}) 13. Bxf4 Nc7 {Black moves his knight towards d4.} 14. Qe1 {The queen will be perfectly placed on g3.} Ne6 15. Bd2 Nd4 16. Qg3 {White has superior pawn structure and some attacking prospects.} *

