{[%evp 0,29,24,8,45,45,70,39,40,5,8,5,23,9,17,14,14,9,22,20,14,-9,15,-10,18,13,9,15,34,39,34,39]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. O-O g6 7. Bxc6 {A well-timed exchange. It practically forced Black to play 7... Bxc6.} (7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bg7 {is less precise because it makes ...bxc6 more attractive for Black. For instance,} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. c5 O-O 11. cxd6 exd6 {the bishop pair provides Black excellent compensation for some structural drawbacks.}) 7... Bxc6 ({After} 7... bxc6 $2 8. e5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 $16 {Black's position is very difficult in view of weak c-pawns.}) 8. d4 $1 {The most energetic. This thematic advance needs no preparation.} cxd4 ({Riskier is} 8... Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 10. Re1 Bf5 $1 {Definitely the best.} ({After} 10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 cxd4 12. Qxb7 {White will be able to regain the pawn and maintain the initiative.}) (10... d5 11. Ne5 Bg7 12. Qa4+ {, followed by 13.Nd7+ feels highly unpleasant for Black.}) 11. Bg5 Qc7 {This position occurred in Jarmula, L - Kacprzak,K Warsaw 2021 White should have opened a second front with} 12. b4 $1 $146 O-O-O {Black's king isn't safe, but this is the lesser evil.} ({Worse is} 12... h6 13. Bf4 Bg7 14. bxc5 $16) 13. Qa4 Kb8 14. bxc5 dxc5 15. dxc5 {This unbalanced position isn't that clear, but White's practical task is easier because of decent attacking prospects.}) 9. Nxd4 Bg7 (9... Bxe4 $2 10. Re1 Bc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qf3 {is practically lost for Black in view of double attack on f6 and c6.}) 10. Qd3 {The most flexible way of covering e4. White is aiming to connect his rooks.} ({For some reason,} 10. Re1 {is much more common, although after} O-O 11. b3 Qa5 12. Bb2 e6 {Black doesn't seem to face difficulties - at some point the freeing ...d6-d5 should follow.}) 10... O-O 11. b3 a6 (11... Qa5 {, as in Das,S - Karthik,V Lignano Sabbiadoro 2022 can be well met by} 12. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 (12... Bxd5 13. exd5 {is even worse.}) 13. exd5 Bd7 14. Bd2 {Now it is clear, that Qa5 backfires - White gains an important tempo.} Qc5 15. Be3 $14 {Black's bishop pair doesn't fully compensate for White's big space advantage and pawn majority on the queenside.}) (11... Rc8 {also yields White time for completing development. The pressure on c4 isn't sufficient because of b2-b3.} 12. f3 Nd7 {The knight's transfer on c5 is among Black's key ideas in such positions but is actually a temporary activity.} ({Hardly better is} 12... Qa5 13. Be3 e6 14. Rac1 $14 {Hlavac, R - Jandl,V Klatovy 2014}) 13. Be3 Nc5 14. Qd2 a6 15. Rad1 $14 {Black's counterplay with b7-b56 is still questionable, and White can choose between a few promising plans such as b2-b4, f3-f4, or even h2-h4-h5.}) (11... Nd7 {The immediate knight' transfer on c5 forces White to take off central pawn, but it doesn't really offer Black any counter-attacking abilities.} 12. Be3 Nc5 13. Qc2 Rc8 ({After} 13... Ne6 14. Rad1 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bxd4 16. Rxd4 {White's knight is superior over the bishop and Black's king isn't fully safe.}) 14. Rac1 Ne6 15. Rfd1 Qa5 16. Nde2 {A decent manoevre: White is interested in maintaining the tension, even though the exchange on d4 wouldn't fully solve opponent's issues.} b5 17. Qd2 $1 {exploiting vulnerability of Black's queen. Black's ability to play b7-b5 turns insufficient.} bxc4 18. Nd5 Qd8 19. Rxc4 {White's positional advantage is undeniable.}) 12. Rd1 $1 {This flexible is more precise} ({than} 12. Bb2 Rc8 13. Nd5 Bd7 14. Rfe1 b5 $132 {Jarmula,L - Chigaev, M Chess.com INT 2022}) 12... Rc8 13. f3 {This is the point. White strenghtens e4 and secures e3 for the bishop.} Qa5 14. Be3 e6 15. Rac1 {Black struggles to solve his space issues because d6-d5 will create new weaknesses.} *

