{[%evp 0,37,25,24,45,45,61,40,40,5,15,11,15,3,18,7,18,18,17,9,25,24,12,9,2,2,41,-15,11,0,12,8,18,22,23,15,17,4,0,21]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 {This position is often reached with 4.Bxd7+ Nxd7, e.t.c. In similar to 4...a6 5.Bxd7+ Nxd7 I prefer to deviate from immediate confrontation in centre and keep the position closed.} 7. d3 Bg7 8. h3 O-O {Hardly there is anything more sensible at Black's disposal.} ({In the event of} 8... Ne5 9. Nxe5 dxe5 10. Be3 Nd7 11. a3 {, followed by b2-b4 White has an easy play on the queenside.}) 9. Be3 Rc8 (9... a6 10. O-O {transposes to 4...a6.}) ({The other natural move is} 9... Qc7 10. O-O e6 (10... Ne5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. a3 {looks nice for White, in similar to 8...Ne5.}) 11. Qd2 Rfd8 12. Bh6 {The exchange of bishops will make Black's king more exposed, and it offers White decent attacking chances. A likely plan is Nh2,f2-f4, e.t.c} Bh8 13. Rae1 a6 14. Ng5 $36 {Black's pieces on the kingside are rather cramped, and White should be able to quickly extend his initiative.}) 10. O-O Nb8 {Black's knight is heading on c6 to take more control of d4. This is a sensible idea, but it takes a few tempi.} (10... Ne5 11. Nxe5 dxe5 12. a3 $14) 11. Qd2 Nc6 12. Rae1 $1 {White fully focuses on his attacking actions, but it makes sense to keep the bishop on e3 for a while.} ({Somewhat premature is} 12. Bh6 e6 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Nh2 d5 $1 {, and Black is just on time to make a counterplay.}) 12... e6 13. Nh2 {White declares his intent to play f2-f4.} b6 ({After} 13... Nd4 14. Bh6 Bxh6 15. Qxh6 b6 16. f4 {White's play on the kingside is lasting faster.}) 14. Bh6 Ne8 {Black is aiming to stabilize the situation in view of the upcoming f2-f4.} 15. Bxg7 Nxg7 16. f4 f5 17. exf5 gxf5 ({After} 17... Rxf5 18. g4 Rf7 19. Nf3 $14 {White has more space, and e6 is weaker than f4.}) 18. Nf3 Qf6 19. Rd1 $1 {White is ready to claim the opponent's structural drawbacks with d3-d4.} *

