{[%evp 0,31,24,24,45,45,68,30,34,5,11,15,15,18,29,19,19,7,3,0,-5,-7,-12,-12,8,-3,24,31,39,35,21,23,50,33]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 {This is by far the most common way of meeting 4.c4. Black invites White to enter the main tabiya with 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 and then at some White captures on d7.} 6. Bxd7+ Qxd7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 {Since 8.Nxd4 often leads to the exchange of knights, I find this recapture sensible: Since White has a traditional space advantage, it makes sense to deviate from simplifications.} Bg7 (8... Nc6 9. Qd3 Ng4 10. O-O Bg7 {transposes to 8...Bg7.}) 9. O-O O-O ({The minor alternative line is} 9... Nc6 10. Qd3 {In most cases Black castles, but there are some independent cases} Rc8 ({After} 10... Ng4 11. b3 f5 {It makes sense to deviate from fianchetto with} 12. Bd2 $1 (12. Bb2 {is weaker in view of} f4 $1 13. Qd2 Nge5 {control over e5 provides Black excellent play.}) 12... O-O ({Nearly the same type of position arises after} 12... fxe4 13. Qxe4 O-O 14. Rad1 $14) 13. h3 Nge5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Qg3 {White has the traditional structural advantage. Black's best attempt to complicate the matters is} fxe4 16. Nxe4 d5 17. cxd5 Qxd5 18. Rae1 {, but it looks like White should be able to neutralize some activity of the opponent and retain a plus.}) 11. Rb1 $1 {A decent consolidating move that allows White to connect the pawns with b2-b3.} ({The routine} 11. Bd2 {is now less precise in view of} Ng4 12. b3 b5 $1 {It turns out, that Black saves a tempo for 0-0 and manages to emerge a decent counterplay.} 13. cxb5 Nb4 $132) 11... O-O (11... Ng4 {doesn't change anything:} 12. b3 Nge5 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. Qd2 $14 {with a follow-up like Bb2,Nd5,f4. Black's position remains passive.}) 12. b3 {From now White can choose between 13.Bb2 and other squares along c1-h6 diagonal.} a6 ({After} 12... Qd8 13. Bd2 Re8 14. Rbc1 Nd7 15. Rfd1 {White managed to stabilize situation and prevent any attempt to make counterplay with b7-b5 and d6-d5. Laduke, M - Sternik, R FICGS email 2021}) 13. Bd2 $5 {I prefer this way of development.} ({In case of} 13. Bb2 e6 $1 ({Pointless is} 13... Nb4 $6 14. Qe2 {, and then} b5 $2 15. a3 Nc6 16. cxb5 axb5 17. Nxb5 {jusrt leaves Black a pawn down.Prabhu, N - Al Hosani,O Chess.com INT 2022}) 14. Rfd1 Rfd8 15. h3 Qc7 {It is not so easy to increase the pressure on d6.}) 13... e6 14. Rfd1 {is another interesting possibility. Black still struggles to play the freeing d6-d5.} Qc7 15. Rbc1 Rfd8 16. h3 {Black has to do with both ..Bf4 and Bg5. White is firmly in  control.}) 10. Qd3 {Obviosuly, White's queen doesn't have to stay on the same diagonal with Black's fianchettoed bishop.} Rc8 {A classical approach,  similar to some lines with 4.Bxd7+ - Black leaves the knight undeveloped in order to immediately put pressure on the c4-pawn.} ({The other ways to deviate from 10...Nc6 are:} 10... Na6 {Black's knight is heading on c5, as usual.} 11. Qe2 Rac8 (11... Nc5 12. Bg5 {it makes sense to provoke the weakening h7-h6} h6 13. Bd2 Rac8 14. Rad1 $14 {White's pieces are placed harmoniously, and Black struggles to challenge the pawn centre.}) 12. Bg5 h6 ({Black achieves nothing special by means of} 12... Nc5 13. Rad1 Na4 14. Nxa4 Qxa4 15. b3 $14) 13. Bd2 Qe6 14. b3 Nc5 {The massive attack on e4 looks annoying, but White cna do with it.} 15. Rae1 a6 16. h3 {Black's queen is now misplaced, and ...b7-b5 is problematic in view of Nf3-d4.}) (10... a6 {is hardly well-timed as Black still cannot play b7-b5} 11. Bg5 $1 {White develops the bishop actively. One of the key ideas is to pin the d6-pawn and then push e4-e5.} h6 {This was Wojtaszek,R - So,W Chess.com INT 2022 White should have played} 12. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 13. Nd5 $16 {Black cannot avoid significant damage of pawn structure because of threat 14.Nb6.}) 11. Bd2 {White's knight needs to be supported in view of further b2-b3.} Na6 (11... Nc6 {transposes to Mainline.}) 12. Qe2 Qc6 {Black reaches maximum activity, but it is still not enough to equalize.} 13. b3 Nc5 14. Rae1 {Covering e4 and moving the rook away from dangerous opposition with g7-bishop. From now Black has to deal with Nc3-d5 manoevre.} e6 {Quite a committing move, but Black takes control of d5.} 15. e5 Ne8 16. Rd1 $14 {Black's position is solid but rather passive. White benefits from opening the d-file because his rook is already placed there. Svane,R - Bjerre,J Havana 2023} *

