{[%evp 0,33,21,22,45,47,67,30,40,13,15,15,18,18,18,29,26,0,-9,-10,-18,-18,-15,-2,0,-19,42,10,34,72,73,77,84,86,79,76]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Bxd7+ Qxd7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 $5 (8. Nxd4 Bg7 {will get us back to the above-mentioned theoretical position, which mostly arises after 4.Bxd7+.}) 8... Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qd3 Nc6 {This is one of key positions of 4.c4 line. It can be also reached with various move orders, such as 8...Nc6.} 11. Bd2 {White connects the rooks and overprotects c3-knights, so Black's counter-attacking abilities are limited now.} a6 {Black clearly shows his intention to prepare ...b7-b5.} (11... Rfc8 {is a standard setup of rooks for Maroczy type of positions.} 12. Rac1 Qd8 {Black vacates d7 for his knight, while the queen is heading on a5.} 13. b3 Nd7 14. Rfd1 a6 ({In the event of} 14... Nc5 15. Qe2 a6 {White can initiate active play on the kingside with} 16. h4 $5 {The further extension with h4-h5 is quite annoying, while} h5 17. Bg5 Ne6 18. Be3 $14 {White has excellent prospects in centre - Black has to do with both ..Nc3-d5 and e4-e5 and lacks any active ideas.}) 15. Nd5 {White loses a tempo, but practically forces Black to weaken his pawn chain with e7-e6.} (15. Qe2 $5 {is another promising idea.}) 15... e6 {It is hard to do with such an active d5-knight for too long.} 16. Nc3 Nde5 (16... Nc5 17. Qe2 $14) 17. Nxe5 dxe5 18. Qxd8+ Rxd8 19. Be3 {Black had no proper compensation for White's pawn majority on the queenside. Navara,D - Mamedov,R Baku 2021}) ({The other natural continuation is} 11... Rac8 12. b3 a6 (12... Ng4 {was tried in a couple of games. It doesn't seem to provide Black any additional counter-attacking chances:} 13. h3 $146 {The most forcing.} Nge5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Qe2 $14) 13. Rac1 Rfd8 {This setup is only sensible in case Black can play ...e7-e6 and d6-d5, but here it doesn't work.} 14. Rfd1 Ng4 15. Nd5 $14 {Black was doomed to passive defence in Kamsky, G - Jacobson, B Chess.com INT 2022}) (11... Rad8 {Black concesses attempt to make counterplay with b7-b5, but White has to fight with a possible f7-f5 break.} 12. Rad1 $1 {Therefore, it makes sense for White to keep the rook on the kingside.} ({Less precise is} 12. Rfd1 Qe6 $1 13. Rac1 Nd7 {, and Black is well-prepared for active actions with f7-f5.}) 12... Ng4 ({After} 12... Qe6 13. Ng5 Qe5 14. b3 h6 15. Nf3 Qh5 16. h3 $14 {Black's queen feels clearly misplaced, and counter-attacking abilities are questionable.}) 13. b3 {This consolidating move has to be played at some point.} f5 {This was Navara, D - Grandelius, N Prague 2021 Now the simple} 14. exf5 $146 Rxf5 15. h3 Nge5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Qg3 $14 {leaves Black with no real compensation for inferior pawn structure.}) 12. Rfd1 Rab8 {The most consistent.} ({After} 12... Rfd8 13. h3 Rac8 14. Rac1 h6 15. Be3 $14 {White had a slight, but long-lasting positional advantage in Laduke, M - Vollmer, S FICGS email 2021}) 13. Rac1 b5 {The ability to play this move is Black's undeniable achievement. Even so, it doesn't seem to fully solve the issues.} 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Bg5 $1 {White's knight is ready to land on d5 anytime soon.} ({Less promising is} 15. Nxb5 Ne5 16. Nxe5 Qxb5 $132) {A likely continuation here is} 15... b4 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nd5 {The b2-pawn is untouchable in view of Rxc6. The threat of Nxf6+ makes Black's position rather uncomfortable.} *

