{[%evp 0,27,22,38,45,41,59,40,33,15,15,15,17,27,24,16,22,12,5,-32,-8,-26,1,-26,4,0,3,-7,1,-10]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. O-O Be7 (6... a6 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 {transposes to 4...a6 & 5...Nbxd7}) 7. Bxd7+ {A well-timed exchange. Black is now invited to show his cards.} Nbxd7 ({After} 7... Qxd7 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. Qe2 {Black can hardly favorable deviate from ...a7-a6 that will transpose to 4...a6} Nc6 11. Be3 {We will conseder some attempts to deviate from a7-a6:} Rfe8 (11... Rac8 12. Rad1 a6 {transposes to 4...a6.}) ({After} 11... Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Qc6 13. f4 e5 14. Nd5 $1 {White has the better chances due to superior bishop.}) (11... Rfd8 12. f4 Rac8 13. Rad1 Qc7 {, as in Rublevsky, S - Klimov, S Krasnoyarsk 2003 can be well met by} 14. Ndb5 $1 Qb8 15. g4 a6 16. Nd4 {Balck is missing pieces around his king. White's potential expansion looks threatening.}) 12. Rad1 Rad8 13. f4 Qc7 14. Kh1 a6 {We have been following the game Rublevsky, S - Kalinin, A Moscow 2002 Now the most energetic was} 15. g4 $1 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Nd7 ({Hardly better is} 16... e5 17. Bg1 exf4 18. g5 Nd7 19. Nd5 $36) 17. g5 Qc6 18. b3 {White's pieces are ready to join the attack, while Black's counterplay is problematic.}) 8. d3 (8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. b3 {is another common way of handling the position.}) 8... O-O ({An equal alternative is} 8... Ne5 {Black accepts the double pawns in order to put pressure on opponent's backward pawn d3.} 9. Ne1 {At his turn, White makes f2-f4 possible and maintains the tension.} O-O 10. f4 Nc6 11. g4 {There is no reason for delaying this move. By playing g4-g5 White diminishes Black's control of d5.} Nd7 12. Bd2 $1 {A flexible move. White is getting closer for connecting the rooks.} ({Premature is} 12. g5 e5 $1 {[%csl Rf4,Rg5]} 13. Nf3 exf4 14. Bxf4 Nde5 {Black has decent counterplay against g5. Hakobyan,A - Shankland,S Saint Louis 2023}) 12... Bf6 13. Nf3 a6 ({After} 13... Nd4 14. g5 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 Bd4+ 16. Kh1 a6 17. a4 {Black's counterplay is limited, and the king gets under long-termed pressure.}) 14. a4 $1 ({Instead,} 14. g5 Bd4+ 15. Kh1 b5 $132 {allows too much activity on the queenside.}) 14... Qc7 {This position was reached in Gatterer, F - Piacenti, L ICCF email 2022 here I like the prophylactic} 15. Rb1 $5 $146 {White unpins the c3-knight and makes b2-b4 possible in case Black moves his c6 knight.} Rae8 {Black reasonably mobilizes his forces around the king.} ({Another point of 15. Rb1 is that} 15... Rab8 16. g5 Bxc3 17. bxc3 {makes it no possible to play ... b7-b5, so Black's position remains rather passive.}) 16. Ne2 g6 17. h4 {White has interesting attacking ideas with h4-h5, g4-g5, and so on. Objectively, it is about equal, but Black's practical task seems tougher.}) ({In the event of} 8... a6 {White can play} 9. Kh1 {with transposition to 4...a6.} (9. Ne1 $5 {is possible too.})) 9. Ne1 ({This time} 9. Kh1 {in analogy to 4...a6 is somewhat slow, so Black can quickly initiate play in centre by means of} Ne5 10. Ng1 d5 11. f4 Nc6 $132) 9... a6 {Black declares his intent to play ... b7-b5, even if it will cost him a pawn.} (9... Ne5 {transposes to 8...Ne5}) (9... d5 {is an ambitious attempt to make counterplay in centre, but after} 10. f4 dxc4 (10... d4 11. Ne2 e5 12. Ng3 $14) 11. dxc4 Nb6 12. Qxd8 Rfxd8 13. b3 $14 {Black suffers from lack of space and poor b6-knight.}) 10. f4 b5 11. Nf3 $1 ({It makes a little sense to accept the sacrifice:} 11. cxb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 c4 $1 {[%csl Rd3,Re4] White's pawn centre is now destroyed, and Black has plenty of play on the a and b files.}) 11... b4 ({After} 11... bxc4 12. dxc4 Qc7 13. b3 {Black's counterattacking abilities are very limited, and White's space advantage is significant.}) ({The same can be said about} 11... Qb6 12. Kh1 Qb7 13. Qe2 Rad8 14. b3) 12. Ne2 {White's knight moves towards g3 or f4.} Nb8 13. h3 Nc6 14. g4 {A complex struggle is ahead. I like White's attacking prospects.} *

