{[%evp 0,31,38,38,45,37,70,39,39,15,13,17,13,2,39,34,12,46,64,51,51,36,36,-5,57,58,45,58,76,65,82,92,90,60]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ Bd7 4. c4 g6 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 (5... Nxd7 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. d3 Ngf6 8. h3 {transposes to 4...Nf6 & g6.}) 6. d4 {This move shouldn't be delayed.} ({After} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. d4 cxd4 {White cannot recapture with his queen.}) 6... Bg7 {Only this move has an independent value. Black takes} (6... cxd4 7. Qxd4 Nf6 8. Nc3 {transposes to 4...Nf6 & g6.}) 7. d5 $1 ({After} 7. Nc3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nf6 {we enter another tabia. It can be also reached with 4.Bxd7+ Qxd7 5.c4, e.t.c.}) 7... Qg4 {This is the most challenging reaction - Black attacks both pawns simultaneously, although it costs him few tempi.} ({The other attempt to challenge White' centre is} 7... b5 8. O-O bxc4 {, but after} 9. Na3 $1 Nf6 ({After} 9... c3 $6 10. bxc3 Bxc3 11. Rb1 {White's initiative was too strong in Meier,G - Fernandez,D Chess.com INT 2020}) 10. Re1 O-O 11. Nxc4 Qb7 12. Rb1 $14 {Whtie still has superiority in space and decent prospects in centre with .. e4-e5.}) ({The quieter} 7... Nf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O {leads to a typical position a-la Benoni, when Black's queen is clearly misplaced.} a6 ({The attempt to quickly develop counterplay on the queenside with} 9... b5 {Atakisi, U - Kanakaris,G Veliko Gradiste 2018 meets} 10. e5 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Qf5 12. Re1 $36 {Black struggles to complete development in view of strong e5-knight.}) 10. e5 Ng4 {, as in De Filomeno,S - Di Paolo,R Acqui Terme 2013 runs into} 11. exd6 $146 exd6 12. Bf4 b5 13. h3 Nf6 14. Nd2 {White's pieces are much better coordinated, and weakness of d6-pawn starts to tell.}) 8. O-O Qxe4 9. Qb3 b6 ({I also examined} 9... Nd7 $5 {Now it is a pity to waste a tempo for capturing b7, and it is more promising to quickly mobilize all the forces:} 10. Nc3 Qf5 11. h3 Ngf6 12. Re1 $44 {White has excellent compensation for the pawn, when pawns b7 and e7 are under pressure, and Black's queen is clearly misplaced.}) 10. a4 $1 $146 {This energetic continuation is an improvement} ({over} 10. Re1 Qf5 11. a4 Nd7 12. h3 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 {Black managed to consolidate in Evans, S - Caruso,A ICCF email 2017}) 10... Nd7 11. h3 $1 {White covers g4 square and offers Black to show his cards.} ({Instead, the consistent} 11. a5 bxa5 12. Nc3 Qf5 13. Nb5 Kf8 14. Rxa5 a6 {leads to unclear consequences.}) 11... Ne5 (11... Ngf6 {is well met by} 12. Nbd2 Qf5 13. Ra3 $1 {White is threatening to trap opponent's queen with g2-g4.} ({The immediate} 13. g4 Nxg4 14. hxg4 Qxg4+ 15. Kh1 Qh3+ {leads to unclear consequences.}) 13... Ne5 (13... g5 14. Re1 O-O 15. Nf1 {provides White interesting compensation for the pawn.}) 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. a5 {White manages to regain the pawn in favorable situation when Black's pawn structure has some defects.}) 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. a5 {It is a good moment for acting actively on the queenside.} bxa5 14. Rxa5 Kf8 ({The careless} 14... Nf6 $2 {meets} 15. Bh6 $1 {, and Black's king is in big trouble in view of ..Qb7.}) 15. Nd2 Qf5 16. Qb7 {I am not sure if White is objectively better here, but he manages to regain the pawn and maintain activity. An interesting struggle is ahead.} *

